**What is the feature or improvement you would like to see?**

A guarantee that I can call `igraph_setup()` multiple times in the same program without any bad things happening. 

Ideally, all invocations besides the first should be a no-op. From inspecting the code in `src/core/setup.c`, this is currently the case in practice, but it would be nice for this to be an explicit behavior of the function in the [official docs](https://igraph.org/c/html/main/igraph-Basic.html#igraph_setup).

**Use cases for the feature**

I have some (C++) libraries that call **igraph** internally. I would like to call `igraph_setup()` within my functions so that users of my libraries don't have to worry about calling it at the start of their program - they don't even know that **igraph** is running under the hood, so it would be odd to ask them to call `igraph_setup()`. Specifically, if I can safely call `igraph_setup()` multiple times, I can just throw it at the start of each of my functions. This ensures that any internal calls to the **igraph** library will be valid whenever one of my functions is called.

Currently I do something like:

```cpp
void my_function() {
    static bool has_setup = false;
    if (!has_setup) {
        igraph_setup(); // omitting the check of the return value for now
        has_setup = true;
    } 
    // Use igraph functions safely.
}
```

Which is fine for a single function, but doesn't protect against multiple calls to `igraph_setup()` from other functions or libraries.

(It's worth noting that my functions manually set the **igraph** RNG type/seed, so technically, I don't even need to call `igraph_setup()` right now. However, the ["Added" section of the release notes](https://github.com/igraph/igraph/releases/tag/1.0.0) suggests that more functionality might be added to `igraph_setup()` in the future, so I'd like to future-proof my code for upcoming releases; hence my questions on this function's "official" behavior.)

`igraph_rewiring_stats_t` looks like this now:

```c
typedef struct {
    igraph_int_t successful_swaps;

    /* unused members added at the end to allow us to extend the stats in the future
     * without breaking ABI compatibility. Do not use this field in your own code */
    igraph_int_t _unused[7];
} igraph_rewiring_stats_t;
```

C does not guarantee packing all these `igraph_int_t` values tightly in the struct. There may be padding. This means that making `_unused` have length 6 and adding another `igraph_int_t` member may change the size of the struct.

I suggest adding separate `igraph_int_t` members, let's have about 4 in total. At this time I have two more possible `igraph_int_t` values in mind that we might start recording.
